      "writtenOn": "2020-09-29T17:51:08Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Nit, feel free to ignore: Consider using an interface here.\n\nThe main rationale is that the TriggeredJob class in the generated JavaScript code is never used because there are no calls to \"new TriggeredJob()\". Instead, an object literal is used on lines 113-117. Note that this means the default values for the class fields are never used either.\n\nSee the compiler output here: https://www.typescriptlang.org/play?ssl\u003d1\u0026ssc\u003d1\u0026pln\u003d1\u0026pc\u003d6#code/MYGwhgzhAEAqBOBLA5sgpvNATAUgewCNoBvAKGmgDswBbNALmggBclLloBeaAIh4G5y0YHho1EzRizYdufQRURYprROy68BpAL6lSIyi2irUGbPgIRGCFOky5CAbQC6Gx0LIUK1Oox4AxPDweABohChExCT8AQTj4hNDw6CU-AEYkim0QkmSfBl4AITB4TK9I8Ukiwpra2rLFZV4AJjLdZ0EgA.\n\nIn other words, it seems like the TriggeredJob type\u0027s purpose is to describe the shape of our data, which is what interfaces are great for, as opposed to e.g. bundling data and behavior together, which we would typically do with a class.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 26,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 26,
        "endChar": 5
      },
      "revId": "a5254854104d3326a9a6ccb703d77af0b3444606",
